=== Tong&#x27;s modification of Kummer&#x27;s test===

A new version of Kummer&#x27;s test was established by Tong. See also 
for further discussions and new proofs. The provided modification of Kummer&#x27;s theorem characterizes
all positive series, and the convergence or divergence can be formulated in the form of two necessary and sufficient conditions, one for convergence and another for divergence.

* Series formula_42 converges if and only if there exists a positive sequence formula_185, formula_186, such that formula_187

* Series formula_42 diverges if and only if there exists a positive sequence formula_185, formula_186, such that formula_191 and formula_192

The first of these statements can be simplified as follows:

* Series formula_42 converges if and only if there exists a positive sequence formula_185, formula_186, such that formula_196

The second statement can be simplified similarly:
* Series formula_42 diverges if and only if there exists a positive sequence formula_185, formula_186, such that formula_200 and formula_192

However, it becomes useless, since the condition formula_202 in this case reduces to the original claim formula_203

=== Frink&#x27;s ratio test ===
Another ratio test that can be set in the framework of Kummer&#x27;s theorem was presented by Orrin Frink 1948.

Suppose formula_204 is a sequence in formula_205,
* If formula_206, then the series formula_207 converges absolutely.
* If there is formula_208 such that formula_209 for all formula_168, then formula_211 diverges.

This result reduces to a comparison of formula_211 with a power series formula_213, and can be seen to be related to Raabe&#x27;s test.

